  "prompt": "What is covered and uncovered interest parity?",
  "response": "Covered interest parity (CIP) and uncovered interest parity (UIP) are fundamental concepts in international finance that explain the relationship between interest rates and exchange rates.\n\n### Covered Interest Parity (CIP)\n\nCovered interest parity asserts that the difference in interest rates between two countries should be equal to the differential between the forward exchange rate and the spot exchange rate. It suggests that there should be no arbitrage opportunities available due to discrepancies in interest rates when hedging is taken into consideration. \n\nMathematically, it can be expressed as:\n\n\\[\n(1 + i_d) = \\frac{F}{S}(1 + i_f)\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( i_d \\) = interest rate in the domestic country\n- \\( i_f \\) = interest rate in the foreign country\n- \\( F \\) = forward exchange rate (foreign currency per unit of domestic currency)\n- \\( S \\) = spot exchange rate (foreign currency per unit of domestic currency)\n\nUnder CIP, if an investor engages in a currency swap using the forward market, they can ensure that the returns on investments in different currencies will be equivalent when the returns are converted to a common currency.\n\n### Uncovered Interest Parity (UIP)\n\nUncovered interest parity, on the other hand, is a theory that relates interest rate differentials and expected changes in exchange rates without a hedge. It posits that the expected change in the exchange rate between two currencies over a specific period should equal the interest differential between those two currencies.\n\nMathematically, it can be represented as:\n\n\\[\nE(S_t) = S_0 \\left(1 + i_d\\right) / \\left(1 + i_f\\right)\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( E(S_t) \\) = expected future spot exchange rate\n- \\( S_0 \\) = current spot exchange rate\n- \\( i_d \\) = interest rate in the domestic country\n- \\( i_f \\) = interest rate in the foreign country\n\nUnder UIP, if an investor chooses to invest in a currency without covering the exchange rate risk (i.e., no forward contracts), the risk arising from the potential change in exchange rates should compensate for the interest rate differentials.\n\n### Key Differences\n\n1. **Hedging**: CIP involves hedging against exchange rate risk using forward contracts, while UIP does not.\n2. **Risk**: UIP incorporates the potential risks and uncertainties related to exchange rate fluctuations, while CIP assumes that arbitrage opportunities will be exploited, establishing a no-arbitrage condition.\n\nIn essence, both concepts highlight the interconnectedness of interest rates and exchange rates in international finance, but they operate under different assumptions concerning risk management.",
